{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513736"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:13:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:13:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12204"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12204","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12204"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.07,0.51,0.22,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4732"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56963"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4732","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4732"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12204"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42412"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1780"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7460"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8696"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8724"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16948"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17648"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56963","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56963"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 82-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with her daughter, having been recently diagnosed with chronic lymphocytic leukaemia (CLL). The patient is worried about potential complications related to the CLL that she may face in the future. Her medical history includes hypertension and type 2 diabetes, both of which are well controlled. She does not take any regular medications for her CLL.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following events is she at the highest risk of experiencing?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Frequent episodes of nosebleeds","New onset skin or gastrointestinal lesions","Recurrent episodes of fever and chills","Sudden onset of severe headache and visual disturbances","Development of a second cancer"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn patients with chronic lymphocytic leukaemia (CLL),\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003Erecurrent episodes of fever and chills\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0are very suggestive of an increased risk of infections. CLL lymphocytes are dysfunctional and often cannot produce antibodies, which increases the risk of infection. Patients are often deficient in IgG, IgA, and IgM, this is termed \u003Cem\u003Ehypogammaglobulinaemia\u003C/em\u003E. This patient\u0027s comorbidities, such type 2 diabetes, may further increase the risk of infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFrequent episodes of nosebleeds\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0can be a symptom of various haematologic conditions causing a primary haemostasis deficit, including thrombocytopenia or platelet dysfunction. CLL can cause thrombocytopenia in rare cases due to bone marrow failure or via CLL-induced immune thrombocytopenic purpura (ITP).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENew onset skin or gastrointestinal lesions\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0might suggest secondary malignancies, which are a rare complication of CLL. There is an increased risk of other malignancies such as skin, gastrointestinal and lung cancers in patients with CLL. However, infections remain the most common complication in these patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESudden onset of severe headache and visual disturbances\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0are symptoms that could be associated with hyperviscosity syndrome. This is a rare complication of CLL that can occur when there is an extremely high white cell count (\u0026gt;300,000/\u00b5L).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile there is an increased risk of\u00a0\u003Cstrong\u003Edevelopment of a second cancer\u003C/strong\u003E\u00a0in CLL patients, this is not as immediate or frequent a risk as infections. A related phenomena is Richter\u0027s transformation, where CLL transforms to a highly aggressive diffuse B-cell lymphoma. Richter\u0027s transformation is associated with poor clinical outcomes. Additionally, the cancer can also predispose the development of non-Hodgkin\u0027s lymphoma, acute myeloid leukaemia, and non-blood cancers such as melanoma, lung cancer and bladder cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most common complications in patients with Chronic Lymphocytic Leukaemia (CLL) occur due to their dysfunctional lymphocytes that cannot produce antibodies, resulting in a deficiency of IgG, IgA, and IgM and this leads to recurrent infections.","Patients with CLL are also at risk of the development of other cancers, and the progression to diffuse B-cell lymphoma is known as Richter\u0027s transformation."],"references":["Dearden C. Disease-specific complications of chronic lymphocytic leukemia. Hematology. 2008;2008(1):450\u20136.","Mukkamalla SKR, Taneja A, Malipeddi D, et al. Chronic Lymphocytic Leukemia. [Updated 2023 Mar 7]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470433/","Leukemia \u0026 Lymphoma Society. Complications of CLL or CLL treatment. Leukemia \u0026 Lymphoma Society. n.d. Available from: https://www.lls.org/leukemia/chronic-lymphocytic-leukemia/treatment/complications-cll-or-cll-treatment"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42412"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12204"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42412","links":{